description: Taxus wallichiana var. yunnanensis is a subspecies of the Himalayan yew tree, which is a coniferous evergreen plant species native to the Yunnan province of China. It is a small to medium-sized tree, typically growing to a height of 10-20 meters. The leaves are needle-like, dark green in color, and arranged spirally on the branches. The plant produces small, fleshy, red fruits called "arils" that surround a single, hard seed. Taxus wallichiana var. yunnanensis is known for its slow growth rate and its ability to thrive in mountainous, shaded environments. The plant is valued for its wood, which is highly durable and resistant to decay, as well as for its potential medicinal properties, as some compounds found in the plant have been studied for their anti-cancer and other therapeutic effects.
